0447194 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=suzuki-toru>{{cite book|last=Suzuki |first=T\u014dru \u9234\u6728\u4ea8 |authorlink=<!--:ja:\u9234\u6728\u4ea8 (\u6b74\u53f2\u5bb6)--> |title=Nihonshi kawaraban |script-title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u53f2\u74e6\u7248 |publisher=Sansh\u016bsha<!--\u4e09\u4fee\u793e --> |year=2006 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Of7oe4ENX8oC&pg=PA167 |page=167|isbn=9784384038323 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=toriyama-eng>{{citation|last=Toriyama |first=Sekien |authorlink=Toriyama Sekien |translator=Hiroko Yoda |translator2=Matt Alt |title=Japandemonium Illustrated: The Yokai Encyclopedias of Toriyama Sekien |publisher=Courier Dover Publications |year=2017 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oeTtDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA168 |pages=168 |isbn=9780486818757 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=yoda&alt2013>{{citation|last=Yoda |first=Hiroko |authorlink=<!--Hiroko Yoda--> |last2=Alt |first2=Matt |authorlink2=<!--Matt Alt--> |title=Yokai Attack!: The Japanese Monster Survival Guide |publisher=[[Tuttle Publishing]] |year=2013 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ArQAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT265 |pages=265 |isbn=978-1-462-90883-7}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Citation | url = http://digidol.llgc.org.uk/METS/MST00001/frames?div=0&subdiv=0&locale=en&mode=thumbnail | publisher = LLGC | title = 17th century pamphlet telling the story of an alleged sighting of a mermaid near Pendine, Wales, in 1603 | place = [[United Kingdom|UK]]}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Briggs |first=K. M. |authorlink=Katharine M. Briggs |title=An Encyclopedia of Fairies, Hobgoblins, Brownies, Boogies, and Other Supernatural Creatures |publisher=Random House |year=1976 |isbn=0-394-73467-X}}\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20090401003144/http://www.gtj.org.uk/en/small/item/GTJ64526/ Older archived version], with brief synopsis and commentary\n* J\u00f8n, A. Asbj\u00f8rn, [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/280883413_Dugongs_and_Mermaids_Selkies_and_Seals Dugongs and Mermaids, Selkies and Seals]\n* {{cite journal|ref=harv|last=Waugh |first=Arthur |author-link=Arthur Waugh |title=The Folklore of the Merfolk |journal=Folklore |volume=71 |number=2 |date=<!--Jun.-->1960|url= |pages=73\u201384 |doi=10.1080/0015587x.1960.9717221 |jstor=1258382}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Wood |first=Juliette |authorlink=Juliette Wood |chapter=Ch. 2: Lingering in sea caves: The world of the mermaid |title=Fantastic Creatures in Mythology and Folklore: From Medieval Times to the Present Day |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |year=2018 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=48tjDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA49 |pages=49\u201392 |isbn=1-441-13060-8}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.amnh.org/exhibitions/mythic-creatures/water/becoming-mermaids |title=Becoming Mermaids |last= |first= |date= |website=amnh.org |publisher=American Museum of Natural History |access-date=1 October 2019 |quote= }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.weird.unnaturalhistorymuseum.org/mermaids/ |title=Mermaid Report Room |last= |first= |date= |website=UnnaturalHistoryMuseum.org |publisher=Lumberwoods, Unnatural History Museum |access-date=1 October 2019 |quote= }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Fairies}}\n{{Heraldic creatures}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Human-headed mythical creatures]]\n[[Category:Mermaids| ]]\n[[Category:Heraldic beasts]]\n[[Category:Medieval legends]]\n[[Category:Nereids]]\n[[Category:Water spirits]]\n[[Category:Therianthropy]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:2790:deb0:34ff:de4:aff6:b3b8", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mermaid"}
{"title_page": "Mahavir Janma Kalyanak", "text_new": "{{use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox holiday\n|holiday_name = Mahaveer Janma Kalyanak \n|image = File:Vardhaman Keezhakuyilkudi.jpg\n|caption = Vardhaman Mahaveer image at Keezhakuyilkudi, Madurai, Tamilnadu, India.\n|nickname = Translation: Birth Anniversary of Lord Mahavir; Mahaveer Janma Kalyanak\n|observedby = [[Jain]]s\n|date = ''Chaitra Sud Triyodashi'' ([[Vira Nirvana Samvat]])\n|observances = Prayers, [[Jainism#Worship and rituals|religious rituals]]\n|celebrations = Going to the [[Jain Temple]]\n|longtype = Religious, [[India]] (National holiday)\n|significance = Birth Anniversary of [[Mahaveer]] Swami\n|date2020 = 6 April (Monday)<ref>https://www.timeanddate.com/holidays/india/mahavir-jayanti</ref>\n|date2021 = 25 April (Sunday)<ref>https://www.timeanddate.com/holidays/india/mahavir-jayanti</ref>\n|frequency=Annual\n}}\n{{Jainism}}\n'''''Mahavir Janma Kalyanak''''' or '''Mahavir Jayanti''' is one of the most important religious festivals in [[Jainism]]. It celebrates the birth of [[Mahavira|Mahavir]], the twenty-fourth and last ''[[Tirthankara]]'' of present ''[[Avasarpi\u1e47\u012b]]''.{{efn|descending half of the worldly time cycle as per [[Jain cosmology]] which is actually current now}} As per the [[Gregorian calendar]], the holiday occurs either in March or April.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9dNOT9iYxcMC |title=Concise Encyclopaedia of India|first=K.R.|last=Gupta|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist |date= 2006|accessdate=6 May 2017|isbn=9788126906390|p=1001 }}</ref> It is also known as 'Veer Teras,' highlighting the 13th 'Sud' day of the Chaitra month of the [[Jain calendar|Jain Calendar]]\n\n==Birth==\nAccording to [[Jain literature|Jain texts]], Mahavir was born on the thirteenth day of the bright half of the moon in the month of ''[[Chaitra]]'' in the year 599 BCE (Chaitra Sud 13).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KpBuAAAAMAAJ|title=Gazetteers: Junagadh|last1=(India)|first1=Gujarat|year=1975|p=13}}</ref><ref>Kristi L. Wiley: ''Historical Dictionary of Jainism'', Lanham 2004, p. 134.</ref> Most modern historians consider Vajji (which is today's Vaishali district of Bihar) as his birthplace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2003-10-14/patna/27173208_1_kundalpur-lord-Mahaveera-basokund|title=Row over Mahaveer\u2019s birthplace|work=The Times of India}}</ref> Mahavir was born in a democratic kingdom (Ganarajya), Vajji, where the king was chosen by votes. [[Vaishali district|Vaishali]] was its capital.{{sfn|Jalaj|2011|p=4}}\n\nMahavir was named 'Vardhamana', meaning \"One who grows\", because of the increased prosperity in the kingdom at the time of his birth.{{sfn|Kailash Chand Jain|1991|p=32}} In Vasokund, Mahavir is revered by the villagers. A place called ''Ahalya bhumi'' has not been ploughed for hundreds of years by the family that owns it, as it is considered to be the birthplace of Mahavir.{{sfn|Jalaj|2011|p=4}}\n\n===Legend===\n[[File:Sixteen Symbolic Dreams.jpg|thumb|left|Sixteen auspicious dreams seen by the mother of all ''Tirthankara'']]\nMahavirswami was born into [[Ikshvaku dynasty]] as the son of King [[Siddhartha of Kundagrama]] and Queen [[Trishala]]. During her pregnancy, Trishala was believed to have had a number of [[auspicious dreams]], all signifying the coming of a great soul. [[Digambara]] sect of Jainism holds that the mother saw sixteen dreams which were interpreted by the King Siddhartha.{{sfn|Pannalal Jain|2015|p=460}} According to the [[Svetambara]] sect, the total number of auspicious dreams is fourteen. It is said that when Queen Trishala gave birth to Mahavir, [[Indra]], the head of heavenly beings (''[[Deva (Jainism)|devas]]'') performed a ritual called ''abhisheka on Sumeru Parvat'', this being the second of five auspicious events (''[[Panch Kalyanaka]]s''), said to occur in the life of all ''[[Tirthankara|Tirthankaras]]''.<ref>{{citation|last=Pramansagar|first=Muni|title=Jain tattvavidya|year=2008|publisher=Bhartiya Gyanpeeth|location=India|isbn=978-81-263-1480-5|p=30}}</ref>\n\n==Celebrations==\n[[File:Thirakoil-mahaaveerar.JPG|Ancient image of Lord Mahavir at [[Thirakoil]]|thumb|250px|right]]\nThe idol of Lord Mahavir is carried out on a chariot, in a procession called ''[[Ratha Yatra|rath yatra]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/469429/piety-marks-mahaveer-jayanthi.html|title=Piety marks Mahaveer Jayanthi|work=Deccan Herald}}</ref> On the way stavans (religious rhymes) are recited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freepressjournal.in/both-sects-of-jain-community-take-out-attractive-joint-procession/|title=Both sects of Jain community take out attractive joint procession|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406193847/http://www.freepressjournal.in/both-sects-of-jain-community-take-out-attractive-joint-procession/|archivedate=6 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Statues of Mahavir are given a ceremonial anointment called the [[Abhisheka#Abhisheka as a ritual|''abhisheka'']].  During the day, most members of the [[Jain community]] engage in some sort of charitable act, prayers, pujas, and [[Vrata|vratas]]. Many devotees visit temples dedicated to Mahavir to meditate and offer prayers.<ref>{{citation |title=Mahaveer Jayanti 2015: The importance of a Satvik meal |url=http://food.ndtv.com/food-drinks/mahavir-jayanti-2015-the-importance-of-a-satvik-meal-751655 |work=[[NDTV]] |date=2 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404075153/http://food.ndtv.com/food-drinks/mahavir-jayanti-2015-the-importance-of-a-satvik-meal-751655 |archivedate=4 April 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Lectures by monks and nuns are held in temples to preach the path of virtue as defined by [[Jainism]]. Donations are collected in order to promote charitable missions like saving cows from slaughter or helping to feed poor people. Ancient Jain temples across India typically see an extremely high volume of practitioners come to pay their respects and join in the celebrations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/lifestyle/culture/story/who-is-mahavir-why-is-mahavir-jayanti-celebrated-1200290-2018-03-29|title=How and Why Mahavir Jayanti is celebrated|last=|first=|date=|website=India Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAhinsa runs and rallies preaching Lord Mahavir's message of [[Ahimsa in Jainism|Ahi\u1e43s\u0101]] (non-violence) are taken out on this day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merinews.com/article/jain-youth-to-hold-vegan-promotion-rally-on-mahavir-jayanti-in-pink-city-jaipur/15905383.shtml|title=Jain youth to hold vegan promotion rally on Mahaveer Jayanti in pink city Jaipur|work=merinews.com |date=28 March 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-jains-gear-up-for-mahavir-jayanti-tomorrow-2073618|title=Jains gear up for Mahaveer Janma Kalyanak tomorrow|date=1 April 2015|work=dnaindia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/over-900-run-for-spreading-bhagwan-mahaveers-message/article7047517.ece|title=Over 900 run for spreading Bhagwan Mahaveer\u2019s message|author=Staff Reporter|work=The Hindu |date=30 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Religion|Holidays}}\n{{refbegin|2}}\n*[[Diwali (Jainism)]]\n*[[Jain rituals]]\n*[[Jain festivals]]\n*[[Kshamavani]]\n*[[God in Jainism]]\n*[[Parshvanatha]]\n*[[Digambara]]\n*[[Timeline of Jainism]]\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{citation |last=Jain |first=Kailash Chand |authorlink=Kailash Chand Jain |title=Lord Mah\u0101v\u012bra and His Times |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8-TxcO9dfrcC |date=1991 |publisher=[[Motilal Banarsidass]] |isbn=978-81-208-0805-8 |ref={{sfnref|Kailash Chand Jain|1991}} }}\n* {{citation|last=Jain |first=Pannalal |title= Uttarapur\u0101\u1e47a of \u0100ch\u0101rya Gu\u1e47abhadra |date=2015 |publisher= [[Bhartiya Jnanpith]] |author-link=Pannalal Jain |isbn=978-81-263-1738-7 |ref={{sfnref|Pannalal Jain|2015}} }}\n* {{citation |last1=Jalaj |first1=Dr. Jaykumar |title=The Basic Thought of  Bhagavan Mahavir |year=2011 |publisher=[[Hindi Granth Karyalay]] |location=Mumbai |isbn=978-81-88769-41-4 }}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fas.harvard.edu/~pluralsm/affiliates/jainism/article/antiquity.htm History of Jainism]\n*[http://www.fas.harvard.edu/~pluralsm/affiliates/jainism/quote/quote1.htm Lord Mahavira Sayings]\n*[http://www.theholidayspot.com/mahavirjayanti/mahavir_jayanti_the_festival.htm The Significance of Mahavir Janma Kalyanak]\n\n{{Jainism topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:March observances]]\n[[Category:April observances]]\n[[Category:Jain festivals]]\n", "text_old": "{{use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox holiday\n|holiday_name = Mahaveer Janma Kalyanak \n|image = File:Vardhaman Keezhakuyilkudi.jpg\n|caption = Vardhaman Mahaveer image at Keezhakuyilkudi, Madurai, Tamilnadu, India.\n|nickname = Translation: Birth Anniversary of Lord Mahavir; Mahaveer Janma Kalyanak\n|observedby = [[Jain]]s\n|date = ''Chaitra Sud Triyodashi'' ([[Vira Nirvana Samvat]])\n|observances = Prayers, [[Jainism#Worship and rituals|religious rituals]]\n|celebrations = Going to the [[Jain Temple]]\n|longtype = Religious, [[India]] (National holiday)\n|significance = Birth Anniversary of [[Mahaveer]] Swami\n|date2020 = 6 April (Monday)<ref>https://www.timeanddate.com/holidays/india/mahavir-jayanti</ref>\n|date2021 = 25 April (Sunday)<ref>https://www.timeanddate.com/holidays/india/mahavir-jayanti</ref>\n|frequency=Annual\n}}\n{{Jainism}}\n'''''Mahavir Janma Kalyanak''''' or '''Mahavir Jayanti''' is one of the most important religious festivals in [[Jainism]]. It celebrates the birth of [[Mahavira|Mahavir]], the twenty-fourth and last ''[[Tirthankara]]'' of present ''[[Avasarpi\u1e47\u012b]]''.{{efn|descending half of the worldly time cycle as per [[Jain cosmology]] which is actually current now}} As per the [[Gregorian calendar]], the holiday occurs either in March or April.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9dNOT9iYxcMC |title=Concise Encyclopaedia of India|first=K.R.|last=Gupta|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist |date= 2006|accessdate=6 May 2017|isbn=9788126906390|p=1001 }}</ref> It is also known as 'Veer Teras,' highlighting the 13th 'Sud' day of the Chaitra month of the [[Jain calendar|Jain Calendar]]\n\n==Birth==\nAccording to [[Jain literature|Jain texts]], Mahavir was born on the thirteenth day of the bright half of the moon in the month of ''[[Chaitra]]'' in the year 599 BCE (Chaitra Sud 13).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KpBuAAAAMAAJ|title=Gazetteers: Junagadh|last1=(India)|first1=Gujarat|year=1975|p=13}}</ref><ref>Kristi L. Wiley: ''Historical Dictionary of Jainism'', Lanham 2004, p. 134.</ref> Most modern historians consider Kundagram (which is today's Kundalpur in Champaran district of Bihar) as his birthplace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2003-10-14/patna/27173208_1_kundalpur-lord-Mahaveera-basokund|title=Row over Mahaveer\u2019s birthplace|work=The Times of India}}</ref> Mahavir was born in a democratic kingdom (Ganarajya), Vajji, where the king was chosen by votes. [[Vaishali district|Vaishali]] was its capital.{{sfn|Jalaj|2011|p=4}}\n\nMahavir was named 'Vardhamana', meaning \"One who grows\", because of the increased prosperity in the kingdom at the time of his birth.{{sfn|Kailash Chand Jain|1991|p=32}} In Vasokund, Mahavir is revered by the villagers. A place called ''Ahalya bhumi'' has not been ploughed for hundreds of years by the family that owns it, as it is considered to be the birthplace of Mahavir.{{sfn|Jalaj|2011|p=4}}\n\n===Legend===\n[[File:Sixteen Symbolic Dreams.jpg|thumb|left|Sixteen auspicious dreams seen by the mother of all ''Tirthankara'']]\nMahavirswami was born into [[Ikshvaku dynasty]] as the son of King [[Siddhartha of Kundagrama]] and Queen [[Trishala]]. During her pregnancy, Trishala was believed to have had a number of [[auspicious dreams]], all signifying the coming of a great soul. [[Digambara]] sect of Jainism holds that the mother saw sixteen dreams which were interpreted by the King Siddhartha.{{sfn|Pannalal Jain|2015|p=460}} According to the [[Svetambara]] sect, the total number of auspicious dreams is fourteen. It is said that when Queen Trishala gave birth to Mahavir, [[Indra]], the head of heavenly beings (''[[Deva (Jainism)|devas]]'') performed a ritual called ''abhisheka on Sumeru Parvat'', this being the second of five auspicious events (''[[Panch Kalyanaka]]s''), said to occur in the life of all ''[[Tirthankara|Tirthankaras]]''.<ref>{{citation|last=Pramansagar|first=Muni|title=Jain tattvavidya|year=2008|publisher=Bhartiya Gyanpeeth|location=India|isbn=978-81-263-1480-5|p=30}}</ref>\n\n==Celebrations==\n[[File:Thirakoil-mahaaveerar.JPG|Ancient image of Lord Mahavir at [[Thirakoil]]|thumb|250px|right]]\nThe idol of Lord Mahavir is carried out on a chariot, in a procession called ''[[Ratha Yatra|rath yatra]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/469429/piety-marks-mahaveer-jayanthi.html|title=Piety marks Mahaveer Jayanthi|work=Deccan Herald}}</ref> On the way stavans (religious rhymes) are recited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freepressjournal.in/both-sects-of-jain-community-take-out-attractive-joint-procession/|title=Both sects of Jain community take out attractive joint procession|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406193847/http://www.freepressjournal.in/both-sects-of-jain-community-take-out-attractive-joint-procession/|archivedate=6 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Statues of Mahavir are given a ceremonial anointment called the [[Abhisheka#Abhisheka as a ritual|''abhisheka'']].  During the day, most members of the [[Jain community]] engage in some sort of charitable act, prayers, pujas, and [[Vrata|vratas]]. Many devotees visit temples dedicated to Mahavir to meditate and offer prayers.<ref>{{citation |title=Mahaveer Jayanti 2015: The importance of a Satvik meal |url=http://food.ndtv.com/food-drinks/mahavir-jayanti-2015-the-importance-of-a-satvik-meal-751655 |work=[[NDTV]] |date=2 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404075153/http://food.ndtv.com/food-drinks/mahavir-jayanti-2015-the-importance-of-a-satvik-meal-751655 |archivedate=4 April 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Lectures by monks and nuns are held in temples to preach the path of virtue as defined by [[Jainism]]. Donations are collected in order to promote charitable missions like saving cows from slaughter or helping to feed poor people. Ancient Jain temples across India typically see an extremely high volume of practitioners come to pay their respects and join in the celebrations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/lifestyle/culture/story/who-is-mahavir-why-is-mahavir-jayanti-celebrated-1200290-2018-03-29|title=How and Why Mahavir Jayanti is celebrated|last=|first=|date=|website=India Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAhinsa runs and rallies preaching Lord Mahavir's message of [[Ahimsa in Jainism|Ahi\u1e43s\u0101]] (non-violence) are taken out on this day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merinews.com/article/jain-youth-to-hold-vegan-promotion-rally-on-mahavir-jayanti-in-pink-city-jaipur/15905383.shtml|title=Jain youth to hold vegan promotion rally on Mahaveer Jayanti in pink city Jaipur|work=merinews.com |date=28 March 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-jains-gear-up-for-mahavir-jayanti-tomorrow-2073618|title=Jains gear up for Mahaveer Janma Kalyanak tomorrow|date=1 April 2015|work=dnaindia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/over-900-run-for-spreading-bhagwan-mahaveers-message/article7047517.ece|title=Over 900 run for spreading Bhagwan Mahaveer\u2019s message|author=Staff Reporter|work=The Hindu |date=30 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Religion|Holidays}}\n{{refbegin|2}}\n*[[Diwali (Jainism)]]\n*[[Jain rituals]]\n*[[Jain festivals]]\n*[[Kshamavani]]\n*[[God in Jainism]]\n*[[Parshvanatha]]\n*[[Digambara]]\n*[[Timeline of Jainism]]\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{citation |last=Jain |first=Kailash Chand |authorlink=Kailash Chand Jain |title=Lord Mah\u0101v\u012bra and His Times |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8-TxcO9dfrcC |date=1991 |publisher=[[Motilal Banarsidass]] |isbn=978-81-208-0805-8 |ref={{sfnref|Kailash Chand Jain|1991}} }}\n* {{citation|last=Jain |first=Pannalal |title= Uttarapur\u0101\u1e47a of \u0100ch\u0101rya Gu\u1e47abhadra |date=2015 |publisher= [[Bhartiya Jnanpith]] |author-link=Pannalal Jain |isbn=978-81-263-1738-7 |ref={{sfnref|Pannalal Jain|2015}} }}\n* {{citation |last1=Jalaj |first1=Dr. Jaykumar |title=The Basic Thought of  Bhagavan Mahavir |year=2011 |publisher=[[Hindi Granth Karyalay]] |location=Mumbai |isbn=978-81-88769-41-4 }}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fas.harvard.edu/~pluralsm/affiliates/jainism/article/antiquity.htm History of Jainism]\n*[http://www.fas.harvard.edu/~pluralsm/affiliates/jainism/quote/quote1.htm Lord Mahavira Sayings]\n*[http://www.theholidayspot.com/mahavirjayanti/mahavir_jayanti_the_festival.htm The Significance of Mahavir Janma Kalyanak]\n\n{{Jainism topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:March observances]]\n[[Category:April observances]]\n[[Category:Jain festivals]]\n", "name_user": "Adarshaj03", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahavir_Janma_Kalyanak"}
{"title_page": "M-PHY", "text_new": "{{Infobox computer hardware bus\n| name        = M-PHY\n| fullname    = MIPI M-PHY\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| invent-date = 2011\n| invent-name = [[MIPI Alliance]]\n| super-name  = \n| super-date  = \n| replaces    = [[D-PHY]]\n| width       = 1-4 lanes, w/adaptive discovery (depending on higher-level protocol)\n| numdev      = \n| speed       = up to 11.6 Gbit/s per data lane\n| style       = serial, embedded clock\n| hotplug     = \n| external    = yes, with optical media converter\n| website     = https://mipi.org/specifications/m-phy\n}}\n\n'''M-PHY''' is a high speed data communications [[Physical layer|physical layer]] protocol standard developed by the [[MIPI Alliance]], PHY Working group, and targeted at the needs of mobile multimedia devices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edn.com/design/microwave-rf-design/4210711/MIPI-M-PHY-takes-center-stage |title=MIPI M-PHY takes center stage |publisher=EDN |date= |accessdate=2018-04-22}}</ref>  The specification's details are proprietary to MIPI member organizations, but a substantial body of knowledge can be assembled from open sources.   A number of industry standard settings bodies have incorporated M-PHY into their specifications including [[PCI Express#M-PCIE|Mobile PCI Express]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edn.com/electronics-blogs/eye-on-standards/4418365/M-PCIe---Goin--mobile- |title=M-PCIe \u2013 Goin\u2019 mobile! |publisher=EDN |date= |accessdate=2018-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eecatalog.com/pcie/2012/10/31/pcie-follows-usb-3-0-to-mobile-applications/|title=PCIe Follows USB 3.0 to Mobile Applications - PCI Express|website=eecatalog.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eecatalog.com/pcie/2013/02/26/pci-sig-and-mipi-alliance-announce-mobile-pcie-m-pcie-specification/|title=PCI-SIG and MIPI Alliance Announce Mobile PCIe (M-PCIe) Specification  - PCI Express|website=eecatalog.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomshardware.com/news/M-PCIe-M.2-PCIe-3.1-PCIe-4.0-OCuLink,23259.html|title=PCIe for Mobile Launched; PCIe 3.1, 4.0 Specs Revealed|date=28 June 2013|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pcisig.com/sites/default/files/files/PCI-SIG%20and%20MIPI%20Alliance%20Announce%20Mobile%20PCIe%20(M-PCIe)%20Specification.pdf |title=Specifications |website=pcisig.com |format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.design-reuse.com/articles/33608/moving-pci-express-to-mobile-m-pcie.html|title=Moving PCI Express to Mobile (M-PCIe)|website=Design And Reuse}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mindshare.com/Learn/Mobile_PCI_Express_(M-PCIe)|title=MindShare - Mobile PCI Express (M-PCIe) (Training)|website=www.mindshare.com}}</ref> [[Universal Flash Storage]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jedec.org/standards-documents/focus/flash/universal-flash-storage-ufs|title=Universal Flash Storage (UFS) - JEDEC|website=www.jedec.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.design-reuse.com/articles/30845/universal-flash-storage-mobilize-your-data.html|title=Universal Flash Storage: Mobilize Your Data|website=Design And Reuse}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fonearena.com/blog/242229/ufs-3-0-standard-released-offers-2x-faster-performance-than-ufs-2-1.html|title=UFS 3.0 standard released, offers 2x faster performance than UFS 2.1|website=www.fonearena.com}}</ref> and as the physical layer for [[USB#SSIC|SuperSpeed Inter-Chip USB]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edn.com/electronics-products/electronic-product-releases/audio-design/4375765/MIPI-Alliance-and-USB-3-0-Promoter-Group-Announce-Availability-of-SuperSpeed-USB-Inter-Chip-Specification |title=MIPI Alliance and USB 3.0 Promoter Group Announce Availability of SuperSpeed USB Inter-Chip |publisher=Edn.com |date=2012-06-20 |accessdate=2018-04-22}}</ref><ref name=\"unh.edu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.unh.edu/testing/mobile/mipi-m-phy|title=MIPI M-Phy Testing Services|date=29 May 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"unh.edu\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mipi.org/specifications/m-phy|title=MIPI M-PHY|website=mipi.org}}</ref><ref name=\"design-reuse.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.design-reuse.com/articles/25764/mipi-m-phy-ip.html|title=MIPI\u2122 MPHY - An introduction|website=Design And Reuse}}</ref><ref name=\"design-reuse.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.design-reuse.com/articles/23887/mipi-m-phy-ip-core.html|title=MIPI M-PHY takes center stage|website=Design And Reuse}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://eecatalog.com/smartphone/2014/02/27/mipi\u00ae-alliance-specifications-drive-4k-and-2k-displays-high-performance-cameras/ |title= Specifications |website=eecatalog.com}}</ref>\n\nTo support high speed, M-PHY is generally transmitted using [[differential signaling]] over [[Impedance matching|impedance controlled traces]] between components.   When use on a single [[Printed circuit board|circuit card]], the use of [[electrical termination]] may be optional.   Options to extend it's range could include operation over a short [[flexible flat cable]], and M-PHY was designed to support optical media converters allowing extended distance between transmitters and receivers, and reducing concerns with electromagnetic interference.<ref name=\"design-reuse.com\"/>\n\n==Applications==\n\nM-PHY (like its predecessor [[D-PHY]]) is intended to be used in high-speed point-to-point communications, for example video [[Camera Serial Interface]]s.   The CSI-2 interface was based on D-PHY (or [[C-PHY]]), while the newer CSI-3 interface is based on M-PHY.   M-PHY was designed to supplant D-PHY in many applications, but this is expected to take a number of years.   \n\nThe M-PHY the physical layer is also used in a number of different high-speed emergent [[Technical standard|industry standards]],  [[DigRF]] (High speed radio interface), [[MIPI LLI]] (Low latency memory interconnect for multi-processors systems), and one possible physical layer for the [[UniPro protocol stack]].\n\n==Signaling speed and gears==\nM-PHY supports a scalable variety of signaling speeds, ranging from 10 kbit/s to over 11.6 Gbit/s per lane.     This is accomplished using two different major signaling/speed modes, a simple low-speed (using [[Pulse-width modulation|PWM]]) mode and high speed (using [[8b/10b encoding|8b10b]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jXSgmhwrX6s&t=30|title=MIPI M-PHY Electrical Characterisation & Challenges by Parthasarathy Raju, Tektronix - part 1|first=|last=MIPIAlliance|date=18 December 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>  Communications goes on in bursts, and the design of both high-speed and low-speed forms allows for extended periods of idle communications at low-power, making the design particularly suitable for mobile devices.\n\nWithin each signaling method, a number of standard speeds, known as \"gears\", is defined, with the expectation that additional gears will be defined in future versions of the standard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jXSgmhwrX6s&t=336|title=MIPI M-PHY Electrical Characterisation & Challenges by Parthasarathy Raju, Tektronix - part 1|first=|last=MIPIAlliance|date=18 December 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Serial buses]]\n[[Category:Computer standards]]\n\n\n{{network-stub}}\n[[Category:Physical layer protocols]]\n[[Category:MIPI standards]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox computer hardware bus\n| name        = M-PHY\n| fullname    = MIPI M-PHY\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| invent-date = 2011\n| invent-name = [[MIPI Alliance]]\n| super-name  = \n| super-date  = \n| replaces    = [[D-PHY]]\n| width       = 1-4 lanes, w/adaptive discovery (depending on higher-level protocol)\n| numdev      = \n| speed       = up to 11.6 Gbit/s per data lane\n| style       = serial, embedded clock\n| hotplug     = \n| external    = yes, with optical media converter\n| website     = https://mipi.org/specifications/m-phy\n}}\n\n'''M-PHY''' is a high speed data communications [[Physical layer|physical layer]] protocol standard developed by the [[MIPI Alliance]], PHY Working group, and targeted at the needs of mobile multimedia devices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edn.com/design/microwave-rf-design/4210711/MIPI-M-PHY-takes-center-stage |title=MIPI M-PHY takes center stage |publisher=EDN |date= |accessdate=2018-04-22}}</ref>  The specification's details are proprietary to MIPI member organizations, but a substantial body of knowledge can be assembled from open sources.   A number of industry standard settings bodies have incorporated M-PHY into their specifications including [[PCI Express#M-PCIE|Mobile PCI Express]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edn.com/electronics-blogs/eye-on-standards/4418365/M-PCIe---Goin--mobile- |title=M-PCIe \u2013 Goin\u2019 mobile! |publisher=EDN |date= |accessdate=2018-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eecatalog.com/pcie/2012/10/31/pcie-follows-usb-3-0-to-mobile-applications/|title=PCIe Follows USB 3.0 to Mobile Applications - PCI Express|website=eecatalog.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eecatalog.com/pcie/2013/02/26/pci-sig-and-mipi-alliance-announce-mobile-pcie-m-pcie-specification/|title=PCI-SIG and MIPI Alliance Announce Mobile PCIe (M-PCIe) Specification  - PCI Express|website=eecatalog.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomshardware.com/news/M-PCIe-M.2-PCIe-3.1-PCIe-4.0-OCuLink,23259.html|title=PCIe for Mobile Launched; PCIe 3.1, 4.0 Specs Revealed|date=28 June 2013|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pcisig.com/sites/default/files/files/PCI-SIG%20and%20MIPI%20Alliance%20Announce%20Mobile%20PCIe%20(M-PCIe)%20Specification.pdf |title=Specifications |website=pcisig.com |format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.design-reuse.com/articles/33608/moving-pci-express-to-mobile-m-pcie.html|title=Moving PCI Express to Mobile (M-PCIe)|website=Design And Reuse}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mindshare.com/Learn/Mobile_PCI_Express_(M-PCIe)|title=MindShare - Mobile PCI Express (M-PCIe) (Training)|website=www.mindshare.com}}</ref> [[Universal Flash Storage]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jedec.org/standards-documents/focus/flash/universal-flash-storage-ufs|title=Universal Flash Storage (UFS) - JEDEC|website=www.jedec.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.design-reuse.com/articles/30845/universal-flash-storage-mobilize-your-data.html|title=Universal Flash Storage: Mobilize Your Data|website=Design And Reuse}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fonearena.com/blog/242229/ufs-3-0-standard-released-offers-2x-faster-performance-than-ufs-2-1.html|title=UFS 3.0 standard released, offers 2x faster performance than UFS 2.1|website=www.fonearena.com}}</ref> and as the physical layer for [[USB#SSIC|SuperSpeed Inter-Chip USB]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edn.com/electronics-products/electronic-product-releases/audio-design/4375765/MIPI-Alliance-and-USB-3-0-Promoter-Group-Announce-Availability-of-SuperSpeed-USB-Inter-Chip-Specification |title=MIPI Alliance and USB 3.0 Promoter Group Announce Availability of SuperSpeed USB Inter-Chip |publisher=Edn.com |date=2012-06-20 |accessdate=2018-04-22}}</ref><ref name=\"unh.edu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.unh.edu/testing/mobile/mipi-m-phy|title=MIPI M-Phy Testing Services|date=29 May 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"unh.edu\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mipi.org/specifications/m-phy|title=MIPI M-PHY|website=mipi.org}}</ref><ref name=\"design-reuse.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.design-reuse.com/articles/25764/mipi-m-phy-ip.html|title=MIPI\u2122 MPHY - An introduction|website=Design And Reuse}}</ref><ref name=\"design-reuse.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.design-reuse.com/articles/23887/mipi-m-phy-ip-core.html|title=MIPI M-PHY takes center stage|website=Design And Reuse}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://eecatalog.com/smartphone/2014/02/27/mipi\u00ae-alliance-specifications-drive-4k-and-2k-displays-high-performance-cameras/ |title= Specifications |website=eecatalog.com}}</ref>\n\nTo support high speed, M-PHY is generally transmitted using [[differential signaling]] over [[Impedance matching|impedance controlled traces]] between components.   When use on a single [[Printed circuit board|circuit card]], the use of [[electrical termination]] may be optional.   Options to extend it's range could include operation over a short [[flexible flat cable]], and M-PHY was designed to support optical media converters allowing extended distance between transmitters and receivers, and reducing concerns with electromagnetic interference.<ref name=\"design-reuse.com\"/>\n\n==Applications==\n\nM-PHY (like its predecessor [[D-PHY]]) is intended to be used in high-speed point-to-point communications, for example video [[Camera Serial Interface]]s.   The CSI-2 interface was based on D-PHY (or [[C-PHY]]), while the newer CSI-3 interface is based on M-PHY.   M-PHY was designed to supplant D-PHY in many applications, but this is expected to take a number of years.   \n\nThe M-PHY the physical layer is also used in a number of different high-speed emergent [[Technical standard|industry standards]],  [[DigRF]] (High speed radio interface), [[MIPI LLI]] (Low latency memory interconnect for multi-processors systems), and one possible physical layer for the [[UniPro protocol stack]].\n\n==Signaling speed and gears==\nM-PHY supports a scalable variety of signaling speeds, ranging from 10 kbit/s to over 11.6 Gbit/s per lane.     This is accomplished using two different major signaling/speed modes, a simple low-speed (using [[Pulse-width modulation|PWM]]) mode and high speed (using [[8b/10b encoding|8b10b]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jXSgmhwrX6s&t=30|title=MIPI M-PHY Electrical Characterisation & Challenges by Parthasarathy Raju, Tektronix - part 1|first=|last=MIPIAlliance|date=18 December 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>  Communications goes on in bursts, and the design of both high-speed and low-speed forms allows for extended periods of idle communications at low-power, making the design particularly suitable for mobile devices.\n\nWithin each signaling method, a number of standard speeds, known as \"gears\", is defined, with the expectation that additional gears will be defined in future versions of the standard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jXSgmhwrX6s&t=336|title=MIPI M-PHY Electrical Characterisation & Challenges by Parthasarathy Raju, Tektronix - part 1|first=|last=MIPIAlliance|date=18 December 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Serial buses]]\n[[Category:Computer standards]]\n\n\n{{network-stub}}\n[[Category:Physical layer protocols]]\n", "name_user": "Burt Harris", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added MIPI standards category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-PHY"}
{"title_page": "Sudhi Koppa", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          =  Sudhi Koppa\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{Birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people. Supply only the year unless the exact date is already widely published, as per WP:DOB. For people that have died, use {{Birth date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = [[Kochi]], [[Kerala]], India\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Actor\n| years_active  = 2011\u2013present\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n \n'''Sudhi Koppa''' is an Indian film actor who appears in [[Malayalam cinema|Malayalam films]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/Sudhi-Koppa-to-play-a-political-extremist/articleshow/49582125.cms |title=Sudhi Koppa to play a political extremist |website=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2015-10-30 |access-date=2016-12-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521090747/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/Sudhi-Koppa-to-play-a-political-extremist/articleshow/49582125.cms |archive-date=2016-05-21 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Paul |first=Nelson K |url=http://english.manoramaonline.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/kavi-udheshichathu-review-asif-ali-biju-menon-thomas-liju-thomas-anju.html |title=Kavi Udheshichathu movie review |website=English.manoramaonline.com |date=2016-10-21 |access-date=2016-12-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202200903/http://english.manoramaonline.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/kavi-udheshichathu-review-asif-ali-biju-menon-thomas-liju-thomas-anju.html |archive-date=2017-02-02 |df= }}</ref> He made his film debut in 2009 with an uncredited appearance in ''[[Sagar Alias Jacky Reloaded]]'' (2009).<ref name=\"MB\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mathrubhumi.com/movies-music/news/sudhi-koppa-actor-mathrubhumi-1.1842044 |title=Waited 17 years to become a familiar face in Cinema |website=Mathrubhumi.com |date=2017-04-02 |access-date=2017-04-18 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419104508/http://www.mathrubhumi.com/movies-music/news/sudhi-koppa-actor-mathrubhumi-1.1842044 |archive-date=2017-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==Personal Life==\n\nSudhi hails from Kochi. His father, who was a government officer had a passion towards drama and owned a drama troupe. Sudhi also started off as a theater artist at Vaikom Thirunal Theatre Group, before forming his own drama troupe called 'Creative Theatre Group'.<ref>{{cite web|author=Biju Cherian Manalethu |url=http://cinetrooth.in/2016/03/02/suddhy-kopa-actor-profile-and-biography/ |title=Suddhy Kopa Actor Profile and Biography |website=Cinetrooth.in |date= |access-date=2016-12-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804042754/http://cinetrooth.in/2016/03/02/suddhy-kopa-actor-profile-and-biography/ |archive-date=2016-08-04 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"MB\" />\n\n==Career==\nSudhi started off doing small roles in multi-starer movies. He played a goon attacking [[Bhavana (Malayalam actress)|Bhavana]] in ''[[Sagar Alias Jacky Reloaded]]'' and one of the students in ''[[Seniors (film)|Seniors]]'' (2011). His theater background helped him secure a role in [[Lijo Jose Pellissery]]'s ''[[Amen (2013 film)|Amen]]''. He played the role of Solomon's friend Sebastian, who tries to woo Solomon's sister played by [[Rachana Narayanankutty]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/M-Towns-own-booze-playlist/articleshow/48556134.cms |title=M- Town\u2019s own booze playlist |website=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2015-08-21 |access-date=2016-12-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160219135324/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/M-Towns-own-booze-playlist/articleshow/48556134.cms |archive-date=2016-02-19 |df= }}</ref> He then played many more small roles in ''[[Manglish (film)|Manglish]]'' and ''[[Sapthamashree Thaskaraha]]'' (2014).\n\nHis breakthrough came in ''[[Aadu (film)|Aadu]]'' (2015), in which he played \"Kanjavu\" Soman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/it-not-honey-rose-srinda-who-plays-lead-aadu-oru-bheegara-jeeviyanu-615434 |title=It is Not Honey Rose but Srinda Who Plays the Lead in 'Aadu Oru Bheegara Jeeviyanu' |website=Ibtimes.co.in |date=2014-11-28 |access-date=2016-12-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105223558/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/it-not-honey-rose-srinda-who-plays-lead-aadu-oru-bheegara-jeeviyanu-615434 |archive-date=2016-11-05 |df= }}</ref> The double-crossing Soman served as an important link between the different story tracks in the movie. He subsequently played an important role as the naive Unni in ''[[You Too Brutus (film)|You Too Brutus]]'' (2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nowrunning.com/movie/16511/malayalam/you-too-brutus/5027/review/ |title=You Too Brutus Review - Malayalam Movie You Too Brutus nowrunning review |website=Nowrunning.com |date=2015-03-22 |access-date=2016-12-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105223723/http://www.nowrunning.com/movie/16511/malayalam/you-too-brutus/5027/review/ |archive-date=2016-11-05 |df= }}</ref>\n\n2016 saw a string of releases in which he had good roles. He played Darwin's henchman Appunni in ''[[Darvinte Parinamam]]'' (2015). He was then seen as Hari and Manu's friend Paul Achayan in ''[[Happy Wedding]]'' (2016).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/happy-wedding-completes-101-days-heres-worldwide-box-office-collection-surprise-hit-photos-690873 |title='Happy Wedding' completes 101 days; here's worldwide box office collection of the surprise hit [PHOTOS&#93; |website=Ibtimes.co.in |date=2016-08-23 |access-date=2016-12-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218184903/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/happy-wedding-completes-101-days-heres-worldwide-box-office-collection-surprise-hit-photos-690873 |archive-date=2017-02-18 |df= }}</ref> He then portrayed the alcoholic Thanka in ''[[Anuraga Karikkin Vellam]]'' (2016), who gets into fights with Abhi and friends.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/Asif-is-Biju-Menons-son-in-his-next/articleshow/49014378.cms |title=Asif is Biju Menon\u2019s son in his next! |website=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2015-09-19 |accessdate=2016-12-24}}</ref> He also essayed the role of a comical thief, Kaimal aka Kai in [[Sajid Yahiya]]'s directorial debut ''[[Inspector Dawood Ibrahim|IDI: Inspector Dawood Ibrahim]]'' (2016).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nowrunning.com/idi-inspector-dawood-ibrahim-shoot-progressing/119445/story.htm |title='IDI - Inspector Dawood Ibrahim' shoot progressing |website=Nowrunning.com |date=2016-04-02 |access-date=2016-12-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601103736/http://www.nowrunning.com/idi-inspector-dawood-ibrahim-shoot-progressing/119445/story.htm |archive-date=2016-06-01 |df= }}</ref> He was last seen as one of Asif Ali's teammates in ''[[Kavi Uddheshichathu..?]]'' (2016).\n\nHe is currently working on ''Third World Boys'', a road movie and ''Theeram''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nowrunning.com/theeram-started-rolling/117771/story.htm |title='Theeram' started rolling |website=Nowrunning.com |date=2016-02-17 |access-date=2016-12-24 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319210529/http://www.nowrunning.com/theeram-started-rolling/117771/story.htm |archive-date=2016-03-19 |df= }}</ref> He is also playing a major role in ''[[Avarude Raavukal]]'' (2017), starring [[Asif Ali (actor)]] and [[Unni Mukundan]], and directed by Shanil Muhammed, who had earlier co-directed ''[[Philips and the Monkey Pen]]'' (2013).\nHe also acted in a small role alongside superstar [[Manju Warrier]] in ''[[Udaharanam Sujatha]]'' (2017), which brought him lot of praise and went on to be a critical and commercial success.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Film !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Sagar Alias Jacky Reloaded]]'' || Attacker||\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Mummy & Me]]'' || College Student||Uncredited Role\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Seniors (film)|Seniors]]'' || College Student||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2013 || ''[[North_24_Kaatham|North 24 Kaatham]]'' || Toddy Shop Patron ||\n|-\n|''[[Amen (2013 film)|Amen]]'' || Sebastian ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2014 || ''[[Manglish (film)|Manglish]]'' || Sahadevan ||\n|-\n|''[[Sapthamashree Thaskaraha]]'' || Gee Varghese ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | 2015 || ''[[Aadu (film)|Aadu]]'' || Kanjavu Soman || \n|-\n|''[[You Too Brutus (film)|You Too Brutus]]'' || Unni   ||\n|-\n|''[[Love 24x7]]'' || Joshy ||\n|-\n|''[[KL 10 Patthu]]'' || Nizam ||\n|-\n|''[[Lord Livingstone 7000 Kandi]]'' || Kakapool ||\n|-\n|''Sahapadi 1975'' ||Vinayan  ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" | 2016 || ''[[Darvinte Parinamam]]'' || Appunni ||\n|-\n|''[[Happy Wedding]]'' || Paul || \n|-\n|''[[Oru Murai Vanthu Parthaya (film)|Oru Murai Vanthu Parthaya]]'' || Kochukuttan ||\n|-\n|''[[Anuraga Karikkin Vellam]]'' || Thanka ||\n|-\n|''[[Guppy (film)|Guppy]]'' || Chink Divakar ||\n|-\n|''[[Inspector Dawood Ibrahim|IDI: Inspector Dawood Ibrahim]]'' || Kaimal ||\n|-\n|''[[Dum (2016 film)|Dum]]'' || Sumesh ||\n|-\n|''[[Kavi Uddheshichathu..?|Kavi Udheshichathu..?]]'' || Dineshan ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"9\" | 2017 || ''[[Alamara]]'' || Justin ||\n|-\n|''[[Lakshyam (2017 film)|Lakshyam]]'' || Lock Lalu ||\n|-\n|''[[Udaharanam Sujatha]]'' || Jayan ||\n|-\n|''[[Oru Mexican Aparatha]]'' || Lonappan ||\n|-\n|''Chicken Kokkachi'' ||Azharudeen  ||\n|-\n|''[[Paippin Chuvattile Pranayam]]'' || Ayyappan ||\n|-\n|''[[Avarude Raavukal]]'' ||  Shanil Muhammed||\n|-\n|''[[Theeram]]'' || Venu ||\n|-\n|''[[Aadu 2]]''|| Kanjavu Soman ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2018 || ''[[Eeda]]'' || Thulaseedharan ||\n|-\n|''[[Padayottam]]'' || Renju ||\n|-\n|''[[Joseph (2018 film)|Joseph]]'' || Sudhi Kaippuzha ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 2019 || ''[[Vaarikkuzhiyile Kolapathakam]]'' || Jokkuttan || \n|-\n|''[[Unda (film)|Unda]]''\n|\n|Cameo Appearance\n|-\n|''[[Sathyam Paranja Viswasikkuvo]]''|| Thamara ||\n|-\n|''[[Porinju Mariam Jose]]'' || Disco Babu ||\n|-\n|''[[Vikruthi]]''\n|Heros' Friend.\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=7205423}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koppa, Sudhi}}\n[[Category:Male actors in Malayalam cinema]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Kochi]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          =  Sudhi Koppa\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{Birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people. Supply only the year unless the exact date is already widely published, as per WP:DOB. For people that have died, use {{Birth date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = [[Kochi]], [[Kerala]], India\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Actor\n| years_active  = 2011\u2013present\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n \n'''Sudhi Koppa''' is an Indian film actor who appears in [[Malayalam cinema|Malayalam films]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/Sudhi-Koppa-to-play-a-political-extremist/articleshow/49582125.cms |title=Sudhi Koppa to play a political extremist |website=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=201